## Interface: 30300
## Title: COA State Plates
## Notes: Suppresses friendly PLAYER nameplates while leaving friendly guardian/pet/NPC nameplates visible, whenever the native Friendly Nameplates option shows them; healer mode is its sub-mode (FriendlyPlates.lua, /coagp). Also offers threat coloring against enemy nameplates - state-tiered glow (no glow when secure, an immediate ambient bloom for the warning cue, a wider saturated shimmer for danger), plus an opt-in Instance Fill option for dungeons/raids - as Enemy Plates' current sub-mode (EnemyPlates.lua, /coaep); tank/DPS view auto-detects from the LFG/LFR role when the game has one, falling back to a manual checkbox otherwise (Core.lua's shared player-role index). v3.3 adds the Mob Aggro Cue: an earlier percentage-based warning (rawPercentage vs. threatCautionPct) reusing the same warning color, symmetric for tank and DPS. v3.4 redesigns the threat glow away from the rotating-dash technique and adds a change-debounce so repeated identical states skip re-applying. v3.4.1 calms the danger glow's motion (fewer, slower particles) and adds a first (coarse) combat pre-filter. v3.4.2 replaces that with the real gate: player must have an actual entry on the mob's own threat table (a genuine nil-check on UnitDetailedThreatSituation, not a combat-flag guess), so coloring never renders based on an unrelated bystander's fight. v3.4.3 adds /coasp log - a Core-owned unified debug log + perf monitor (on|off|status|dump|clear), so the threat-coloring decision path and hot-loop timings can be watched live instead of guessed at. v3.4.4 adds a copyable export popup (/coasp log copy [n]) since WotLK's default chat frame has no text-selection - a real client limitation, not something fixable from inside chat itself. v3.4.5 fixes an over-correction the log surfaced live: a mob the GROUP has genuinely engaged (a party/raid member has real threat on it) no longer goes silent just because the player personally hasn't hit it yet - tank view now correctly shows danger ("go get it") for adds the group is fighting that the tank hasn't picked up. v3.4.6 adds roster visibility to that same scan (logs which units it actually checked and each one's raw isTanking result), since a "found nothing" answer needs to be verifiable, not taken on faith. v3.4.7 fixes the real bug that visibility caught: Core's group roster cache was empty the entire time despite being genuinely grouped - GetNumPartyMembers() wasn't returning a usable count on this client. Switched to GetNumGroupMembers(), matching TurboPlates' own confirmed-working usage on this exact server. v3.4.8: v3.4.7 alone did not fix it - a fresh capture still showed an empty roster while grouped. Confirmed GetNumGroupMembers is a genuine Ascension global (not a TurboPlates-only shim), so the API choice wasn't the problem; RefreshGroupRoster's pcall wrapper was silently swallowing whatever the real failure is. Added a log line inside RefreshGroupRoster itself (raid/party branch, raw API return, final roster) plus error surfacing on the group event handler, and a /coasp roster command to force and print a refresh on demand without needing to leave/rejoin group. Also confirmed via code read that solo combat showing nothing is original v2.6 by-design behavior (threat coloring only ever engages while IsInGroup() is true), not a new regression. v3.4.9: the v3.4.8 diagnostics confirmed the roster/API were correct all along - live capture showed roster genuinely empty for ~13min after a /reload while grouped, then self-correcting once GROUP_ROSTER_UPDATE fired again for real (a classic WotLK PLAYER_ENTERING_WORLD-fires-before-roster-data-settles race), and tank-view danger substitution fired correctly the moment the roster populated. Added a ~2s delayed re-check after PLAYER_ENTERING_WORLD (WotLK has no C_Timer, so a one-shot OnUpdate frame stands in) so this self-corrects automatically instead of depending on luck or a manual /coasp roster. v3.5.0: live capture showed a single displayed mob name swinging between wildly different threat states within a couple seconds, which looked like a bug but every log line only ever printed the mob's name, never its underlying nameplate token or GUID - so there was no way to tell a genuinely volatile threat table apart from the client recycling a pooled plate slot onto a different physical mob sharing the same name. Added ns.DescribeUnit(unit) (name + unit token + short GUID) to every relevant log line so the next capture can prove or disprove that directly. Also confirmed with Battlewrath that one such swing was simply real taunt usage (secure -> danger as taunt's forced aggro decays without backing threat), not a bug. v3.5.1: the v3.5.0 GUID tagging paid off immediately - a capture showed the same mob GUID tracked under BOTH "nameplate1" and "target" tokens simultaneously (this client's nameplate backport re-announcing a targeted mob's plate under "target" via NAME_PLATE_UNIT_ADDED), meaning the same physical plate was being double-processed with two independent state caches - a real candidate for both the state swings and the disappearing-plate reports. Added a plateOwner guard (Frame -> canonical unit token) so a later alias for an already-tracked plate is recognized and skipped instead of double-tracked, in both the ADD/REMOVE handlers and the reclassify tick. v3.5.2: v3.5.1 alone didn't fix it - a fresh capture still showed both "nameplate3" and "target" tokens processed every tick for the same mob GUID. Root cause: UNIT_THREAT_SITUATION_UPDATE/UNIT_THREAT_LIST_UPDATE fire with whatever unit token Blizzard's own event system hands over directly, completely bypassing the v3.5.1 guard (which only covered the ADD/REMOVE/reclassify paths). This is also the highest-frequency of the three entry points, so it was almost certainly the dominant source of the double processing. Applied the same plateOwner check there too - all three ways a unit enters Enemy Plates (add/remove, reclassify tick, threat event) now share one dedup guard - confirmed working live (log shows "skipped, duplicate alias" and Battlewrath confirmed plate visibility held the whole session). v3.5.3: Battlewrath reported the roster not updating when a player joined mid-session, needing a manual /coasp roster to correct - the same PLAYER_ENTERING_WORLD timing race from v3.4.9, just triggered by GROUP_ROSTER_UPDATE instead. Generalized the ~2s delayed re-check to run after any of the group-roster events, not just entering world. v3.5.4 adds /coasp log toggle - a quick on/off flip for live-testing sessions (e.g. flipping logging around specific dungeon pulls) without retyping on/off or tracking current state. v3.5.5 replaces the v3.4.9/v3.5.3 delayed re-check's manual OnUpdate elapsed-time accumulator with C_Timer.After, now that C_Timer is confirmed a genuine Ascension client global (already used directly by TurboPlates) rather than something WotLK 3.3.5 lacks - same ~2s one-shot re-check, but the client's own timer does the waiting instead of this addon polling every rendered frame during that window; Battlewrath: "It gives us basis to use that for other similar event handling. So we don't engrain custom internal clocks when we can have the game do it for us." v3.5.6 adds a loose overload safety valve for raid-scale play (Battlewrath: "Should we build in a suspend when that hangs too much? Raids can have 40 units in the play space... add that insurance now at the very open end (so a long wait), just so we have some catchment when that system balloons/spider-webs.") - Core.lua now measures the reclassify tick's duration unconditionally (not just when /coasp log is on) and exposes ns.IsReclassifyOverloaded(), tripping only above 15ms - far beyond any measured or extrapolated raid-scale cost (~1ms/tick from unit count alone, ~5-6ms/tick worst-case estimate for the group-roster scans at 40-man scale). When tripped, EnemyPlates.lua's OnReclassify skips only the expensive Mob Aggro Cue group scans for that tick; core threat coloring (isTanking/status) is never gated. Self-recovers every tick, no manual reset needed. v3.5.7 shifts logging onto the render side, prompted by Battlewrath: "I think we should shift onto the render side. As whilst we've seen bits. I don't have strong confidence it's working as we desire." Every log line up to this point only ever confirmed the decision layer (GetThreatColorForUnit resolving a state) - the debounce skip and the actual executor calls (SetGlow/ClearGlow/SetHealthBarColor/ClearHealthBarColor) were completely silent, so a debounce misfire or a failed glow/fill application would have been invisible to /coasp log, only catchable by eye at the game client. EnemyPlates.lua's ApplyThreatColorForUnit now logs the debounce outcome and exactly what it dispatches to Core; Core's SetGlow/ClearGlow/SetHealthBarColor/ClearHealthBarColor now log whether a frame actually resolved and which LibCustomGlow technique started/stopped (or errored, or fell back to the static border), closing the loop from decision to actual screen output end to end. v3.5.8 adds /coaep rendertest secure|warning|danger|clear [fill], prompted by Battlewrath asking "Are we able to feed dummy input into it? Like I have a target, then it builds a data stream off them?" - forces a state onto your CURRENT TARGET's plate via the exact same Core executor primitives (SetGlow/ClearGlow/SetHealthBarColor/ClearHealthBarColor) ApplyThreatColorForUnit dispatches to, bypassing GetThreatColorForUnit's real threat-table read entirely. Lets the render pipeline be tested on demand (e.g. on a training dummy) without needing real threat conditions to line up; debug/test-only, doesn't touch threatMode/the group gate/the debounce cache. v3.5.9 moves the render test rig from /coaep to Core's shared /coasp, per Battlewrath's correction ("How come coaep? I'd stated core should carry everything") - matches the same "Core is the executor" principle already used for the player-role index. EnemyPlates.lua now registers its testable states with Core via ns.RegisterRenderTest instead of owning its own parallel command. Also adds /coasp rendertest cycle [delaySeconds], prompted by Battlewrath asking "Can we not just run a test cycle that I kick off? Moving through every testable state with a c-time delay?" - chains C_Timer.After calls to auto-step through every registered state (secure, warning, warning+fill, danger, danger+fill, clear) hands-free, instead of typing each command manually. v3.5.10 fixes two things Battlewrath's live test of the cycle command found: (1) a UX gap - "/coasp rendertest 5" (no "cycle") fell through to the one-off state test with a literal state named "5", printing "unknown state '5'"; a bare number is now accepted directly as cycle-with-that-delay shorthand. (2) a real bug in RenderTestApply's color lookup - it used the classic Lua `condition and A or B` idiom, which breaks whenever the "true" branch's own value is itself falsy (if a threatColorX SavedVariable were ever nil, `stateName == "secure" and nil` evaluates to nil regardless of the match, falling through to "unknown state" for a perfectly valid name). Confirmed live: Battlewrath's /coasp rendertest cycle ran all 6 steps correctly in sequence (proving the cycle engine itself works) but every color-based step reported "unknown state" - the signature of this exact footgun. Rewritten as explicit if/elseif with no idiom to trip over, and split into two distinct messages (unrecognized state name vs. recognized name with missing color config). v3.1: rebranded from "COA Guardian Plates"; both modules are signal/behaviour only, never author content. v3.5.11 (2026-07-09) fixes two things confirmed by Battlewrath's live render test cycle capture (which itself came back clean end to end - secure/warning/warning+fill/danger/danger+fill/clear all fired correctly): (1) FriendlyPlates.lua's NPC/pet/guardian color override had no debounce, unlike Enemy's threat-color path - ApplyNPCColorForUnit called Core's SetHealthBarColor/SetNameColor unconditionally on every 0.5s reclassify tick for every classified friendly NPC/pet with a color configured, harmless visually but newly noisy once v3.5.7's render-side logging started logging every one of those redundant reapplies. Added the same lastAppliedNPCColor/StatesMatch-shaped cache Enemy already uses, wiped on disarm and on unit removal so a later re-enable or a recycled unit token always reapplies fresh. (2) Battlewrath, after the render test: "that log path is too noisy to capture the test" - a real capture mixes the handful of render-test-relevant lines (SetGlow/ClearGlow/SetHealthBarColor/ClearHealthBarColor) in with every other active unit's PERF reclassify tick and IsPotentialThreatUnit lines every 0.5s. /coasp log dump and /coasp log copy now take an optional trailing keyword filter (plain substring against source+message, e.g. "/coasp log dump 30 glow") applied before the count slice, so a capture can isolate exactly the lines that matter instead of scrolling past background noise. v3.5.12 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath, after the debounce/log-filter fixes above: "The first cycle failed. I had to go into color pickers, pick a color for each, then re-run. Instead of it being first initialized with default. So maybe no saved variable for it?" SeedThreatColorDefault already seeds all 3 threatColor keys unconditionally at load, before any slash command can even be typed, so a genuinely nil DB value shouldn't be reachable under normal operation and the exact first-run cause wasn't caught live (logging wasn't on for that attempt) - but GetThreatColorForUnit and RenderTestApply both read COA_GuardianPlatesDB.threatColorX directly with no fallback of their own, unlike the color-picker swatches' own Refresh() (already `COA_GuardianPlatesDB[colorKey] or defaultColor`). If that DB value was ever nil/malformed for any reason, the render would have silently done nothing - color=nil means no glow, no fill, no error - exactly the reported symptom, and manually setting a color via the picker is what would "fix" it since SetColor always writes a fresh well-formed table. Added a single GetConfiguredThreatColor(stateName) helper (falls back to that state's built-in default the moment the DB value is nil) used by both call sites, closing the gap regardless of root cause. v3.5.13 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath: "Texture / properties being constants, if we can / one lookup location we can modify" (still planning to test different LibCustomGlow parameter combinations live via a scratch WeakAura before landing on final numbers). Core.lua's SetGlow used to have each LCG *_Start technique's tuning values (frequency, N/dot-count, scale, xOffset/yOffset, the danger tier's saturation boost, etc.) as inline literal arguments buried in the branch logic, each explained by its own nearby comment. Extracted into one GLOW_STYLE_PARAMS table (one sub-table per style: cue/danger/pixel), field names matching each LCG function's own positional argument order - retuning any value is now a one-line edit to that table instead of hunting through SetGlow's control flow. Same numbers as before this move; purely structural, no visual change. v3.5.14 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath prototyped and live-tuned "Danger"/"Warning" glow looks in WeakAuras (an aurabar with a glow subregion, per the earlier "still need to test with weak aura the lib effects to land on something" plan), then handed over both exports: "safe: Not needed. Focus is the glow effect properties only. Might need to see if you can pad it from the bar boarder 0.5 px or something." Decoded both via weakaura_codec.py and read past the aurabar/texture/spark/border container straight to each aura's subglow subRegion - WeakAuras' own LibCustomGlow-backed glow widget, the same library this addon embeds. Both tuned looks use glowType "Pixel" (warning: 10 lines, frequency -0.05; danger: 30 lines, frequency 0.05 - opposite spin direction, both thickness 1), so both threat tiers now render via PixelGlow_Start instead of the previous ButtonGlow("cue")/AutoCastGlow("danger") split. GLOW_STYLE_PARAMS (added last version) restructured from technique-named keys (cue/danger/pixel) to named-look keys, each carrying its own `technique` field plus tuning, so two looks can share a technique with different numbers - added threatWarning/threatDanger as Enemy Plates' own tuned looks; cue/autocast/pixel kept as generic base entries for any future caller. The WeakAuras prototype's glowLength (20/10) was NOT ported as a literal pixel value - it was tuned against a 148x6.8px scratch aurabar with no fixed relationship to a real nameplate's much smaller health bar, so `length` is left nil and PixelGlow_Start auto-derives a proportional dash length from whatever frame it's actually applied to instead. Also tightened SetGlow's glow-frame anchor padding from +/-2px to +/-0.5px per Battlewrath's border-padding note, matching how the WeakAuras prototype anchored its own glow subregion flush to its background with no extra offset. v3.5.15 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath live-tested v3.5.14's ported glow looks and reported: "The danger glow isn't rendering." Root cause: threatDanger's N=30 deliberately left `length` unset so PixelGlow_Start would auto-derive it via the library's own `floor((width + height) * (2 / N - 0.1))` formula - but that formula goes negative once N reaches 20 (2/30 - 0.1 = -0.033), and LibCustomGlow passes the resulting negative length straight into a Frame:SetSize() call inside its own per-frame OnUpdate script, which fails silently every frame (outside this addon's own pcall around the *_Start call, so nothing showed up in /coasp log either). threatWarning's N=10 stayed under that threshold (2/10 - 0.1 = 0.1, positive), which is why only danger broke. Fixed by giving threatDanger an explicit small positive length (4) instead of relying on the auto-derive formula, which is unsafe for N>=20. v3.5.16 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath, after confirming Ascension_NamePlates (not TurboPlates) is the actual driver: "Shall we add boarder correction? A single color wheel picker for enemy plates?" Ascension_NamePlates is client-embedded with no extractable Lua/.toc source, so whether it even exposes a separate, colorable native border region at all (vs. the border being baked into the health bar's own texture) can't be answered by reading code - it has to be confirmed live. Added /coasp probe [unit] (defaults to target): walks every child frame/region under the unit's real nameplate (now capturing Texture-specific detail - texture path, vertex color, draw layer - alongside the existing FontString text capture) and pops a copyable text dump (Ctrl+A/Ctrl+C, same box /coasp log copy already uses) instead of requiring a /reload + SavedVariables round-trip. Purely diagnostic - the color-wheel picker itself is only worth building once a probe capture shows there's a distinct region to target. v3.5.17 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath's first live /coasp probe capture found only a single Texture region (white, vertexColor 1,1,1,1) and reported "I think I found it. It's a name plate, your target highlight. That is red. (In some conditions.)" then "It'd be white, I can't recreate red right now" - confirming the white capture was simply the highlight in its non-red state, not a miss. But the v3.5.16 probe only ever walked one level deep (plate's direct children/regions, container's direct children/regions) - it never opened up the 4 unnamed Frame children the first capture showed sitting under the health bar container, and a native "target selection highlight" is exactly the kind of thing that would live nested inside one of those rather than as a direct child. Rewrote the walk as a depth-limited (5 levels) recursive descent (WalkProbeTree) that opens every Frame-capable child's own children/regions in turn, tagging each entry with its depth and a slash-separated path so the dump reads as an indented tree instead of an ambiguous flat list - built so that whenever the red state IS reproduced, a follow-up probe will actually surface the nested highlight region instead of stopping short of it. v3.5.18 (2026-07-09) - the deeper probe paid off immediately: Battlewrath's next capture (targeting Moonrage Whitescalp) found it nested inside the health bar - Frame "...aggroHighlight" containing Texture "...aggroHighlightTexture" (Interface/TargetingFrame/UI-TargetingFrame-BarFill), hardcoded vertexColor 1,0,0,1 at layer OVERLAY - Ascension_NamePlates' own native "you have aggro" indicator, entirely separate from this addon's own glow and drawn on top of it. Asked whether to suppress it, recolor it, or leave it and add a separate override; Battlewrath chose recolor. Added ns.GetNativeAggroHighlightTexture/ns.SetNativeAggroHighlightColor/ns.ClearNativeAggroHighlightColor to Core.lua (locates the texture via the health bar's aggroHighlight Lua field + a GetRegions() scan, the same mechanism the probe tool already proved works, rather than guessing a field name for the texture itself) and wired it into EnemyPlates.lua's ApplyThreatColorForUnit (all 3 states, not just warning/danger - the native highlight's own render trigger is independent of our showGlow gate, so whenever it does show, it should carry our color instead of always red), DisarmThreatColors (restores native red so a disabled threatMode doesn't leave our last color stuck on it), and the render test rig (so /coasp rendertest can demo/verify it directly). v3.5.19 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath, watching the native recolor work: "It might be we dispatch of our current glow. Depending how this works. As they was trying to do the same thing" - our own LibCustomGlow effect and the native aggroHighlight were now both signaling the same state, and LibCustomGlow's animation carries a real per-frame OnUpdate cost the native recolor doesn't. Asked what to do about the overlap; answer: "If it works. Set our current to something that doesn't actually render / cost performance. Then work out what that extra signal is good for." ApplyThreatColorForUnit and RenderTestApply now try the native recolor FIRST - only when SetNativeAggroHighlightColor reports it couldn't find the aggroHighlight texture at all (e.g. a nameplate template lacking that frame) does the code fall back to our own animated glow, so a real signal still exists anywhere the native path can't reach. The GLOW_STYLE_PARAMS/SetGlow machinery itself was NOT removed - per Battlewrath's own framing, it's being kept to "work out what that extra signal is good for" as a separate question, with the Needs-action highlight (#197) and healer aggro-shift awareness (#251) considerations already on the table as candidates. v3.5.20 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath's next observation: "This only highlights your current target" and "Can we reuse that texture, so the same one that is on our current target, can [be] seen across the aggro cue group and such." Confirmed: SetNativeAggroHighlightColor already runs group-wide (ApplyThreatColorForUnit processes every active hostile unit, not just target), but Ascension_NamePlates' own logic evidently only ever Shows the aggroHighlight frame on the plate that's your current target - recoloring a Hidden texture elsewhere has no visible effect. Added ns.GetNativeAggroHighlightFrame (split out of GetNativeAggroHighlightTexture, which now builds on it) plus two new test-only primitives, ns.ForceShowNativeAggroHighlight/ns.ClearForcedNativeAggroHighlight, which force the frame's Show()/SetAlpha(1) directly rather than trusting native visibility logic. Wired into a new second render-test module, EnemyPlates.lua's "aggroBroadcast" (registered alongside the existing "threat" module, so /coasp rendertest cycle now runs both back to back) - it force-shows + recolors the native highlight across every currently active hostile plate at once (same ns.activeUnits + ns.IsPotentialThreatUnit filter ApplyThreatColorToAllActive already uses), specifically so Battlewrath can visually confirm whether a forced Show() on a non-targeted plate actually sticks or gets silently fought back by the native driver, before deciding whether "reuse across the group" is buildable as a real feature. Caught and fixed a counting bug during review: the first draft used `local shown = pcall(...)`, which only captures whether the call errored, not ForceShowNativeAggroHighlight's own true/false result - would have silently over-counted every unit as "touched" regardless of whether a native frame was actually found. v3.5.21 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath's next capture (running one-off /coasp rendertest danger then clear, not the full cycle yet) showed zero trace of the aggroBroadcast module (no "Render test (aggro broadcast)" print, no ForceShowNativeAggroHighlight log line anywhere) even though Core's dispatcher broadcasts one-off state commands to every registered module, not just cycle - almost certainly because the client was still running pre-v3.5.20 code (Lua files only reload on /reload, not on save). Separately, and independent of that, the capture also showed a real filter bug worth fixing regardless: every visible mob (multiple Ravenclaw Servants) logged "IsPotentialThreatUnit -> false (UnitAffectingCombat=nil)" continuously - none of them had been pulled - and RenderTestAggroBroadcast had reused IsPotentialThreatUnit (which deliberately requires real combat engagement, see its own v3.4.1 doc note) as its own filter. That meant the broadcast test would always report 0 touched plates on an idle group of mobs, regardless of whether the underlying force-show mechanism works at all - the loop never even reached ForceShowNativeAggroHighlight once. Added ns.IsHostileUnit(unit) - the same hostile+attackable check with the combat requirement dropped - and switched the broadcast test to use it, WITHOUT touching IsPotentialThreatUnit itself (that gate stays exactly as-is for real production coloring). Also flagged for the next live test: the same capture showed SetNativeAggroHighlightColor fail to find a texture on the actual TARGET during the danger step - a different result than the earlier successful Moonrage Whitescalp capture - worth re-testing against an actively-engaged mob specifically, since the native frame may only get lazily populated on a pooled plate the first time it's genuinely been a real target/aggro holder, not present from the start on every plate unconditionally. v3.5.22 (2026-07-09) - that re-test came back and settled it: Battlewrath's next capture showed SetNativeAggroHighlightColor/ForceShowNativeAggroHighlight reporting "not found" 100% of the time, INCLUDING on Moonrage Whitescalp while it was actively tanked and targeted - the exact mob an earlier probe had already proven has this structure. A deterministic, repeatable failure on a known-good plate rules out the lazy-init theory and points at the lookup itself: GetNativeAggroHighlightFrame read `healthBar.aggroHighlight` as a Lua field, a guess based on how the frame's NAME happened to look in the original probe dump - but that probe actually found the frame by enumerating healthBar:GetChildren() positionally, never through that key. Indexing a Lua field that was never actually set just silently returns nil (no error), so this went undetected through every earlier read-through until live play surfaced it. Fixed to try the frame's own predictable global name first (healthBar's own name + "aggroHighlight" suffix, the exact pattern every probe capture has shown), falling back to the same GetChildren() scan the probe tool itself has always used and proven reliable. Also corrected the v3.5.18 doc comment that had stated the wrong claim as fact. v3.5.23 (2026-07-09) - even with the lookup fixed, Battlewrath's next live test showed ForceShowNativeAggroHighlight succeeding at the Lua level (Show()/SetAlpha(1)/SetVertexColor all reporting success) but producing no visible change on screen - Ascension_NamePlates' own logic still governs whether that frame actually renders regardless of what gets called on it, a fight not worth continuing. Battlewrath instead found a real answer inside Ascension's own client, queried via its in-game atlas/dev console: "bonusobjectives-bar-glow-ring", a soft horizontal glow-ring sprite baked into Interface\QuestFrame\bonusobjectives (240x51, texcoords 0.474609-0.943359 / 0.511719-0.611328) - "Same key way design. That's a texture in the game. Can we tint / hand roll that?" Added ns.SetHandRolledGlow/ns.ClearHandRolledGlow to Core.lua: a Texture region this addon creates and owns outright (parented to the health bar, same padding convention as the LibCustomGlow frame), so Show()/Hide()/SetVertexColor are guaranteed to actually apply - no external frame's visibility logic to fight, and no per-frame OnUpdate cost since it's a static tinted texture rather than an animated LibCustomGlow effect. Exposed via a new isolated "handRolledGlow" render-test module (EnemyPlates.lua) operating on target only, kept separate from "threat"/"aggroBroadcast" so it can be eyeballed on its own before any decision about folding it into the real ApplyThreatColorForUnit path or replacing LibCustomGlow's animated glow entirely. v3.5.24 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath's screenshots of the v3.5.23 texture showed it rendering INSIDE the health bar's own bounds (basically just tinting the fill) instead of the desired look: a halo sitting BEHIND and AROUND the plate, extending past the bar's edges. Fixed both causes: (1) the anchor padding was only ±0.5px (same size as the bar itself) - widened substantially (-12/+12 horizontal, -10/+10 vertical) so the texture actually extends beyond the bar's silhouette; (2) the draw layer was OVERLAY (on top of everything) - dropped to BACKGROUND (the lowest layer) so the bar's own fill/border art draws over the overlapping middle portion, leaving only the part spilling past the edges visible as a halo. Exact padding numbers are a first pass pending the next live look, not measured against real nameplate dimensions. v3.5.25 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath, after seeing v3.5.24 render as a real halo for the first time ("Not bad at all, you know."): "Let's play a little with the halo. It wants scaling down a touch. And moving to the right of the anchor. So that the round head on the right is framing the level circle on the right." Padding scaled down (12->9 horizontal, 10->7 vertical) and the whole box shifted right by 6px (added to both TOPLEFT/BOTTOMRIGHT x-offsets, keeping the same width) so the sprite's rounded end lands over the level-circle icon instead of centered on the bar. v3.5.26 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath: "Generally great. The right side round part doesn't fully encapsulate the level indicator. So it could be stretched to the right. And maybe as the alert it wants to be scaled slightly bigger - but if their all the same image but tinted. then just stretched to the right. So the level circle is surrounded by the halo." Deliberately kept one shared size for all 3 states (secure/warning/danger all reuse this texture, just tinted differently - a separate size per state would add real complexity for no asked-for benefit) - stretched the right edge further (BOTTOMRIGHT x: 15->22) so the round head fully wraps the level circle, plus a touch more vertical padding (7->8) for the "scaled slightly bigger" ask. v3.5.27 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath, zoomed into the level-icon corner: "It's almost 100%. If you look to the very right side, it doesn't quite sit central. So moving slightly to the left and maybe down to split the difference. So it looks like a shadow around the key." Shifted the whole box left 3px and down 2px (both anchor offsets moved together, width/height unchanged) to recenter the round head on the level-circle icon. v3.5.28 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath, comparing against the v3.5.26 screenshot: "Now up a touch. Can you see how it is lop sided?" The v3.5.27 shift moved both TOPLEFT/BOTTOMRIGHT y-offsets down together (8/-8 -> 6/-10), which is a uniform shift but left top/bottom padding asymmetric (6px vs 10px) - since the sprite itself isn't perfectly symmetric top-to-bottom, that asymmetry read visually as lopsided as well as too low. Restored symmetric vertical padding (8/-8, matching v3.5.26) while keeping v3.5.27's leftward horizontal shift, fixing both complaints in one move. v3.5.29 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath, once the halo was fully tuned: "Can we wire this in to the glow constant we made? Or do we now have a legacy hidden element to compute?" Both: live testing (v3.5.20-3.5.23) had already proven the v3.5.19 native-first/glow-fallback scheme was silently broken - SetNativeAggroHighlightColor succeeding only ever meant the native aggroHighlight texture exists, not that it's visible (Ascension_NamePlates only Shows that frame on your own current target), so the old "native applied -> suppress our own glow" gate was suppressing real threat signal on every plate except whichever one happened to be targeted. ApplyThreatColorForUnit, RenderTestApply, DisarmThreatColors, and OnUnitRemoved now all route ordinary warning/danger threat state through ns.SetHandRolledGlow/ns.ClearHandRolledGlow (the proven, always-renders, zero-per-frame-cost texture tuned through v3.5.28) instead of the native-gated LibCustomGlow dispatch. SetNativeAggroHighlightColor is still called as a harmless bonus recolor for the rare case the native frame is visible, but no longer gates anything. GLOW_STYLE_PARAMS/SetGlow themselves stay in Core, unused by this path now, kept for the still-open "what's that extra signal good for" candidates (Needs-action highlight #197, healer aggro-shift awareness #251). v3.5.30 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath: "Can we modify the colour? Keep it white so our glow isn't being competed with signal wise." SetNativeAggroHighlightColor was still tinting the native aggroHighlight to match the resolved threat-state color (red/orange/green) as a "harmless bonus" for the rare case it's visible (your own current target) - but with the hand-rolled glow now also tinted per state on the same plate, two independently-timed color signals could show at once and read as noise rather than reinforcement. Both call sites (ApplyThreatColorForUnit, RenderTestApply) now recolor the native frame to a fixed neutral white (NATIVE_AGGRO_NEUTRAL_COLOR) instead of the resolved state color, so if it ever flashes it reads as plain presence, not a second, possibly-inconsistent color cue. v3.5.31 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath: "Shall we add a render test to swap it's colors on the threat system on it's own? I can't test if it works when it already defaults to white outside of conditions." Since production now always recolors the native highlight to the same fixed white, there was no real-condition way to compare the recolor call against anything else. Added a new, state-logic-free render test module ("nativeAggroColor") that forces raw color swatches (white/red/yellow/green/clear) straight at ns.SetNativeAggroHighlightColor on your current target, independent of threat states, purely to let the recolor mechanism itself be visually confirmed. Doesn't force the frame Shown (that was already proven unreliable off Ascension_NamePlates' own visibility logic - see the aggroBroadcast module's doc note), so it's only actually visible while genuinely holding aggro on your real target, same as the production path. v3.5.32 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath's live test (grouped, real combat) settled the open question from v3.5.30/31: the aggroHighlight stayed stock red the whole time despite SetNativeAggroHighlightColor reporting "applied" every time with zero errors - some native code is re-driving the texture's color faster than our one-shot call can hold it, confirmed a real race rather than protection. Chose to pursue a deeper hooksecurefunc-based fix rather than give up or leave dead code. Since hooksecurefunc needs the real function's name and Ascension_NamePlates has no readable source, added two diagnostic tools first: ns.ScanGlobalsForPattern/"/coasp scanglobals <substring>" (walks _G for matching global functions, pops a copyable list) and a speculative hooksecurefunc against a short list of plausible candidate names (UnitFrame_UpdateThreatIndicator - WotLK's own confirmed TargetFrame threat-flash driver; CompactUnitFrame_UpdateAggroHighlight - retail's equivalent, worth checking since the probe's own field naming "aggroHighlight" matches retail's convention rather than WotLK's "threatIndicator"), logging via /coasp log whenever any of them actually fire - purely observational until a real hit is confirmed live. "/coasp aggrohooks" reports which candidates exist on this client at all. v3.5.33 (2026-07-09) - live confirmation: "/coasp scanglobals threat" returned UnitFrame_UpdateThreatIndicator (WotLK's own real threat-flash driver, confirmed by source: `indicator:SetVertexColor(GetThreatStatusColor(status))`), while "/coasp scanglobals aggro" turned up nothing resembling a nameplate-specific update function - ruling out the retail CompactUnitFrame_UpdateAggroHighlight guess entirely. Battlewrath's log then showed "SPECULATIVE AGGRO HOOK FIRED: UnitFrame_UpdateThreatIndicator" firing repeatedly and predictably in real combat, confirming the target. Upgraded the hook from observe-only to a real fix: it now recolors the `indicator` argument to white whenever its own name contains "aggroHighlight" (the nameplate-specific naming - TargetFrame/PartyFrame's own indicators are named "...Flash" instead, so every other frame using this shared function is left untouched). Since hooksecurefunc guarantees running AFTER the native SetVertexColor call on every invocation, this actually wins the race instead of losing it, and being a plain post-hook rather than an override it can't introduce taint the way replacing the function outright would risk. v3.5.34 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath fully rebooted the client after deploying (stronger than /reload, rules out stale code) and confirmed no visible change - still red. The v3.5.33 hook had a silent blind spot: it only logged inside the "name contains aggroHighlight" branch, so "the hook never fires" and "the hook fires constantly on something that isn't a nameplate" both looked like total silence in the log - indistinguishable. UnitFrame_UpdateThreatIndicator is genuinely shared by TargetFrame/FocusFrame/PartyMemberFrame1-4/BossTargetFrame1-4 per its own real callers (UnitFrameThreatIndicator_Initialize) - the 4-firings-per-burst pattern seen live is equally consistent with "these are just the standard party/target frames" as with "nameplates route through here too," and that correlation was never actually proven, only assumed. Made the hook log unconditionally (every invocation's indicator name, matched or not) so the next capture will show definitively whether a real aggroHighlight-named indicator ever passes through this function at all. v3.5.35 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath researched the open race question externally and reported back: "I'd rather work it as a part of the system" rather than keep chasing a hooksecurefunc fix. The research surfaced real prior art confirming the race itself is a known, general WoW client behavior (a mature multi-expansion nameplate-threat addon's own source comment: retail health bars "marked dirty from multiple places for next frame reset so we must recolor posthook" - the same phenomenon we hit), but also showed that on Classic-family clients (the closest public analog to this one) that same addon doesn't fight the race at all - it just sets its own color directly, no hook. Several specific function/table names from that research (CompactUnitFrame_UpdateThreatBorder, THREAT_STATUS_COLORS, nameplateShowThreatGlow) don't match anything our own live /coasp scanglobals sweep found on this client, so they're treated as unverified rather than acted on directly. What's genuinely worth checking: GetThreatStatusColor (a confirmed-real global here) plausibly reads its colors from a global table the way real WotLK FrameXML source does - if so, mutating that table once would make our color the system's own data instead of racing a redraw. ns.ScanGlobalsForPattern only ever matched functions, so a color table would've been invisible to it; added ns.ScanGlobalTablesForPattern + "/coasp scantables <substring>" (e.g. "scantables threat" or "scantables color") as its table-scanning sibling, to check for real before trusting unverified names. v3.5.36 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath ran both scans live: "scantables threat" returned only NumericalThreat display-text frames (Boss1-4/Focus/Target's numeric threat-% widgets) and our own options-panel checkboxes - no color-indexed table; "scantables color" returned the generic UI palette (RAID_CLASS_COLORS, POWER_COLORS, FACTION_BAR_COLORS, etc.) with nothing threat-specific at all. Conclusive negative: no ThreatColor/ThreatBarColor-style global table exists on this client under either substring, so GetThreatStatusColor must compute or hardcode its return values in-function rather than reading one - there's no data table to adopt instead of racing the redraw. Combined with the confirmed-real re-assert race (v3.5.32) and the researched precedent that no real addon fights this race on Classic-family clients (v3.5.35), every avenue for making the native aggroHighlight recolor reliably stick is now exhausted; the hand-rolled glow (already production-primary since v3.5.29) remains the addon's only guaranteed-reliable threat signal. v3.5.37 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath: "Can we feed a function and ask what tables it calls?" A real, different question from v3.5.35/36's _G scans - a color table GetThreatStatusColor captures only as a closure upvalue (a local from its enclosing scope, never assigned to any global name) would be entirely invisible to those, since it's not in _G at all, but Lua's own debug library can still see it: debug.getupvalue(fn, i) walks a function's captured locals by index regardless of scope. Added ns.DumpFunctionUpvalues + "/coasp upvalues <funcname>" (e.g. "upvalues GetThreatStatusColor" or "upvalues UnitFrame_UpdateThreatIndicator") - lists every upvalue's name/type, and for any that are tables, samples their contents (including one level of nested sub-tables, the shape a status-indexed {r=,g=,b=} color table would have). Read-only introspection (debug.get*, never debug.set*) - can't itself change behavior or introduce taint. v3.5.38 (2026-07-09) - FINAL VERDICT on the native aggroHighlight recolor saga. Battlewrath spun up three independent research passes (source-verified against two separate 3.3.5a FrameXML mirrors, plus retail/Cataclysm source, plus WotLK nameplate-addon prior art) while this addon's own real `tfunc UnitFrame_UpdateThreatIndicator` traces (dev console, Ascension_UIDevelopmentTools) captured two live invocations - both `PartyMemberFrame1/2PetFrameFlash`, ordinary party-pet threat-flash traffic, never anything named `aggroHighlight`. Converged verdict: `UnitFrame_UpdateThreatIndicator` is structurally gated on a real unit token (`indicator.unit`/`indicator.feedbackUnit`, feeding `UnitThreatSituation`) that nameplates in this client's underlying model never carry into this function - it cannot be the nameplate aggroHighlight's driver, confirmed rather than assumed, matching every real trace captured. Separately: "aggroHighlight" is a Cataclysm 4.0.1 CompactUnitFrame invention (parentKey-driven, `CompactUnitFrame_UpdateAggroHighlight`), completely absent from stock 3.3.5a - yet a real frame matching that exact name and structure genuinely exists on THIS client (found via live `/coasp probe` on Moonrage Whitescalp back in v3.5.18). Reconciled: Ascension backported or reimplemented something aggroHighlight-shaped, but through a mechanism with no Lua-reachable hook (v3.5.33/34, confirmed wrong target), no mutable color table (v3.5.35/36, clean negative), and no closure upvalue (v3.5.37, blocked by this client's addon sandbox) - nothing this addon can reach from the inside. Retired the hooksecurefunc installation and its OnUnitFrameUpdateThreatIndicator/InstallAggroIndicatorHook machinery from Core.lua, and the SetNativeAggroHighlightColor "harmless bonus" calls from EnemyPlates.lua's production path (ApplyThreatColorForUnit, RenderTestApply) - they were confirmed to be chasing/tinting a function and a redraw that nameplates never route through. The locate/recolor primitives (ns.SetNativeAggroHighlightColor/ClearNativeAggroHighlightColor) and the isolated "nativeAggroColor"/"aggroBroadcast" render-test modules are untouched and remain available as diagnostic tools for any future exploration of the legacy WorldFrame-child-scan approach real WotLK addons like TidyPlates/NotPlater use. The hand-rolled glow texture (v3.5.23-29, tuned through v3.5.28) is now, definitively and permanently, the addon's sole production threat signal. Full research trail: AGGRO_HIGHLIGHT_FINDINGS.md. v3.5.39 (2026-07-09) - REOPENED. A follow-up research pass argues this client is actually a Legion/BfA-era CompactUnitFrame nameplate backport (C-side event layer roughly matching FrostAtom's awesome_wotlk, plus a custom client FrameXML rewrite of CompactUnitFrame's aggro/selection-highlight routines) rather than the plain WotLK path v3.5.38 concluded was unreachable - real corroborating evidence already sitting in this addon's own code: ns.GetHealthBar's first branch checks `plate.UnitFrame.healthBar` before falling back to `plate.healthBar`, written defensively for exactly this case. Counter-evidence: our own live "/coasp scanglobals aggro" sweep never found `CompactUnitFrame_UpdateAggroHighlight` (or anything like it) as a global - inconclusive either way, since a rewritten/renamed/localized function wouldn't show up in a name search. Rather than trust an unverified function name a second time, added ns.WatchNativeAggroHighlight + "/coasp watchaggro [unit]" - hooks the actual, already-confirmed-real aggroHighlight frame/texture INSTANCE directly (hooksecurefunc's table+method-name form, not a global-name guess) and logs a trimmed debugstack every time Show/Hide/SetVertexColor fires on it, so the real driver's name is discovered live rather than assumed from either direction. The v3.5.38 production changes (hand-rolled glow as sole signal) are UNCHANGED pending this test - this is purely additive diagnostic tooling. v3.5.40 (2026-07-09) - the watchaggro probe paid off immediately: Battlewrath's live capture caught the real driver red-handed - `CompactUnitFrame.lua:773 UpdateAggroHighlight`, called via `UpdateAll <- SetUnit <- Ascension_NamePlates\NamePlateDriver.lua:227` - confirming this client really does backport the Legion/BfA CompactUnitFrame nameplate system (CompactUnitFrame.lua itself is packed inside this client's MPQ archives, not a loose readable file, so this could only be confirmed by catching it live). Critically, the watchaggro hook that caught this was already installed on the aggroHighlight TEXTURE INSTANCE's own SetVertexColor method (hooksecurefunc's table+method form), not a guessed global function name - meaning the exact same mechanism, upgraded from logging to recoloring, should actually hold this time, unlike v3.5.33's hook which targeted a function nameplates never even passed through. Upgraded ns.SetNativeAggroHighlightColor from a one-shot color set to a PERSISTENT per-texture post-hook: once installed, it re-applies whatever color is currently "desired" immediately after ANY native SetVertexColor call on that exact texture, with a re-entrancy guard so our own reapply doesn't retrigger itself. ns.ClearNativeAggroHighlightColor now just clears the desired-color record (hooksecurefunc hooks can't be uninstalled, so an absent desired color is the permanent off-switch) rather than a one-shot revert. NOT yet re-wired into ApplyThreatColorForUnit's production path - test first via the existing isolated "nativeAggroColor" render test (`/coasp rendertest` module) or by simply holding real aggro, to confirm the color now actually holds on screen before deciding whether to bring native recolor back as production signal alongside or instead of the hand-rolled glow. v3.5.41 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath, trying to capture live evidence of the v3.5.40 recolor hook holding during real combat: "in 300 events it already ran through. so no budget to catch it." The existing /coasp log dump/copy keyword filter (v3.5.11) only narrows results AFTER they're already stored - routine PERF/reclassify-tick noise still fills the fixed 300-entry ring buffer first, evicting exactly the aggro-related lines a live capture needs before they can ever be read back out. Added a store-time filter: ns.SetLogStoreFilter/ns.GetLogStoreFilter plus "/coasp log filter <substring>|off|status" - when set, ns.Log drops any non-matching entry before it's ever written to the buffer, so the full 300-entry capacity is reserved for exactly the evidence being hunted (e.g. "/coasp log filter aggro" then "/coasp log clear" before a party pull, to guarantee the aggroHighlight/recolor lines survive a noisy fight instead of getting flushed out by background ticks). v3.5.42 (2026-07-09) - Battlewrath found a CurseForge addon (TargetNameplateIndicator) hooking a global "CompactUnitFrame_UpdateAggroFlash" to Hide() the native aggro flash. Treated as unverified rather than copied directly: this client's own live-captured callstack (v3.5.40) names the real function "UpdateAggroHighlight", not "AggroFlash", and shows it as file-local to CompactUnitFrame.lua rather than a plain global - exactly the "renamed/localized function" blind spot v3.5.39 already flagged for name-based hooksecurefunc guesses, so hooking the pasted name would likely just error. Instead of chasing another possibly-wrong name, reused the SAME instance-scoped hooksecurefunc technique already proven live in v3.5.40 (hooking the actual, already-located aggroHighlight FRAME object directly) - but to Hide() it persistently instead of re-asserting a color, which is a simpler and more surefire way to answer Battlewrath's original question ("Can we disable the aggression highlight? And then we could replace it with a second of our own?") than fighting the recolor race. Added ns.SuppressNativeAggroHighlight/ns.ClearNativeAggroHighlightSuppress plus "/coasp suppressaggro on|off [unit]" as a standalone test command - not wired into production yet; confirming it holds live is the next step, then it directly unblocks building the "focus" indicator (task #266). v3.6.0 (2026-07-17): THE AT-SOURCE STREAM - CompactUnitFrame.lua became READABLE (patch-B MPQ extraction on the addons bench), ending the blind era. The whole native plate system turns out to be option-gated via optionTable (assigned by-reference from shared defaults in SetUpFrame:2188): healthBarColorOverride is the FIRST-priority branch of UpdateHealthColor:523 (the staleness leak - native event-driven repaints beating our tick - inverts into our enforcement mechanism), displayAggroHighlight:771 gates the red highlight (suppression by steering, no Show() race - which is what beat v3.5.42), and a complete DORMANT native tank-threat border system exists (tankThreatBorderColor family, UpdateHealthBorder:804, group-gated, role-aware) - "it is the tankThreatBorderColor we wanted all along; repainting was just what we had access to" (Battlewrath). Core gains STEERING PRIMITIVES (per-frame optionTable wrapper with __index fall-through to shared; SetPlateOption/SetPlateColorOverride/SetNativeAggro/RefreshPlateColor+Border; driver recycling auto-cleans - SetUpFrame reset confirmed in source; driver config refresh never writes our fields, source-grepped). NEW MODULE AggroPlates.lua (ns.Aggro) = the distinct tank/aggro surface: steers native borders (role-flipped palettes) + optional native-highlight hide, /coasp aggro on|off|status|hl. Draws nothing, hooks nothing, races nothing. Hand-rolled glow stays parked for #197/#251. v3.6.1 (2026-07-17, Battlewrath's architecture): SATELLITE OWNERSHIP MODEL - core carries ALL machinery baseline-OFF; separate "I care about this" addons are the load surface (WoW's native addon list) each adding a minimal Interface>AddOns config page that flips core switches through the curated public global COAStatePlates (separate addons can't see the private ns). First satellite: COA_StatePlates_Aggro (enable borders / hide native highlight, immediate-apply, state reflected on show). Disable the satellite = core returns to baseline. Slash /coasp aggro stays as the shortcut. Low-risk theorycraft companion addon for Conquest of Azeroth.
